BruteIt

Target IP: 10.10.113.251

Brute, hash crack, and escalate privileges in this box!

Reconnaissance


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard port number. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The default Apache2 webpage is displayed for this application, as shown above. Doing a source-code review does not reveal anything useful. Time for a directory search.


Doing a directory search with the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.113.251/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt reveals /admin directory, as shown above.


And the webpage above is displayed for /admin.


The source-code of this /admin contains an interesting HTML comment, as shown above. There are two usernames john and admin. But I do not have the password. Time to bruteforce it.


Using the command hydra -l admin -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt 10.10.113.251 http-post-form "/admin/index.php:user=admin&pass=^PASS^:invalid", I managed to bruteforce and obtain the password xavier for the user admin.


After logging in with the credential admin:xavier, I gained access to the web application. The webpage above is shown after logging in successfully. Is that a SSH key?


And bingo! It is an encrypted SSH key. Does this belong to the user john -- a username I encountered during enumeration?


I copied the SSH key to my machine and used john to obtain the passphrase rockinroll.

Exploitation


And I successfully gained access to the SSH application as the user john with the SSH key on port 22. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user john.

Privilege Escalation


The binary /bin/cat can be executed without password as the user root. Maybe I can obtain the SSH key of user root or even the shadow file?


Using the binary /bin/cat, I obtained the content of /etc/shadow file. This file contains the password hash $6$zdk0.jUm$Vya24cGzM1duJkwM5b17Q205xDJ47LOAg/OpZvJ1gKbLF8PJBdKJA4a6M.JYPUTAaWu4infDjI88U9yUXEVgL. of user root.


I copied the password hash of user root to my machine and used john to crack it. I obtained the password football for the root user.


And using the password football, I was able to switch user to root successfully. Now I have a root shell on the target machine. GG.
